10 (A) The purpose of the Commission is to make recommendations to improve the
11 delivery of foundational public health services in the State.
12 (B) THE COMMISSION SHALL PROVIDE OVERSIGHT OVER
13 IMPLEMENTATION OF THE COMMISSION’S RECOMMENDATIONS.
14 (C) THE DEPARTMENT SHALL PROVIDE AN UPDATE REGARDING THE
15 IMPLEMENTATION OF THE COMMISSION’S RECOMMENDATIONS TO THE
16 COMMISSION EACH QUARTER.
17 13–5106.
18 (a) The Commission shall assess the foundational public health capabilities of the
19 Department and local health departments in the State.
20 (b) (1) In conducting the assessment required under subsection (a) of this
21 section, the Commission shall:
22 (i) Explain the impact of the foundational public health capabilities
23 on the State’s ability to address foundational public health areas, including as the
24 foundational public health areas relate to behavioral health;
25 (ii) Explain the impact of the foundational public health capabilities
26 on the State’s ability to respond to COVID–19, overdoses, maternal and infant mortality,
27 and other major public health challenges as appropriate; and
28 (iii) Provide public outreach to hold at least three public meetings in
29 different areas of the State that include an opportunity for public comment.
30 (2) In conducting the assessment required under subsection (a) of this
31 section, the Commission may:

HOUSE BILL 1109 11
1 (i) Request deidentified and publicly available data from the
2 Department, local health departments, and the State–designated health data utility; and
3 (ii) Request interviews with State and local health officials.
4 (c) (1) Based on the assessment conducted under subsection (a) of this section,
5 the Commission shall make recommendations for reform in the following areas:
6 (i) Organization of State and local public health departments;
7 (ii) Information technology, information exchange, and data and
8 analytics;
9 (iii) Workforce, including human resources and use of the [medical
10 reserve corps for public health] MARYLAND MEDICAL RESERVE CORPS ESTABLISHED
11 UNDER TITLE 2, SUBTITLE 11 OF THIS ARTICLE;
12 (iv) Procurement, including oversight of contractors;
13 (v) Funding;
14 (vi) Communication and public engagement; and
15 (vii) Any other area considered appropriate by the Commission.
16 (2) The recommendations made under paragraph (1) of this subsection
17 shall include the funding or legislation required to implement the recommendation, if any.
18 (3) The Commission shall justify each recommendation made under
19 paragraph (1) of this subsection based on how the recommendation contributes to the
20 provision of foundational public health services.
21 (4) (i) The Commission shall make a draft of its recommendations
22 available for public comment for 30 days.
23 (ii) The final report of the Commission shall include a response to
24 any substantive public comment received on the draft recommendations.
25 (5) (i) The Commission shall use best efforts to reach consensus on its
26 recommendations.
27 (ii) If the Commission cannot reach consensus on its
28 recommendations, the Commission shall include the opportunity for dissenting comments
29 in the Commission’s final report.
